Surprise Me !












Thomas F. Frist, III



        Source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_F._Frist,_IIIUpdated: 2017-03-18T14:03Z
      
Thomas F. Frist, IIIBornc. 1968Nashville, TennesseeResidenceBelle Meade, TennesseeAlma materPrinceton UniversityOccupationBusinessman, investor, philanthropistSpouse(s)Julie DamgardChildren3Parent(s)Thomas F. Frist, Jr.Patricia C. FristRelativesThomas F. Frist, Sr. (paternal grandfather)Bill Frist (paternal uncle)William R. Frist (brother)Charles A. Elcan (brother-in-law)Thomas F. Frist, III (born c. 1968) is an American heir, businessman, investor and philanthropist from Tennessee. He is the Founder and Managing Principal of Frist Capital, an investment firm.Contents1 Early life2 Career3 Philanthropy4 Personal life5 ReferencesEarly lifeThomas F. Frist, III was born circa 1968 in Nashville, Tennessee.[1] His father, Thomas F. Frist, Jr., is a billionaire who served as the Chairman of the Hospital Corporation of America (HCA).[2] His mother, Patricia C. Frist, served as a director of SunTrust Banks from 2000 to 2010.[3] His paternal grandfather, Thomas F. Frist, Sr., was a co-founder of HCA.[2] His paternal uncle, Bill Frist, served as a Republican Senator from 2003 to 2007.He graduated from Princeton University with a bachelor of arts degree in 1991.[4] He received a masters in business administration from the Harvard Business School in 1997.[4]CareerFrist was a managing partner at FS Partner, an investment firm based in New York City.[1][2] He also worked for Rainwater, Inc., Richard Rainwater's investment firm, both in New York City and Fort Worth, Texas.[1]Frist founded Frist Capital, another investment firm, in 1998.[4][5] He serves as its Managing Principal.[4][6] In January 2015, the firm invested US$100 million in Bulow Clinic Partners Group, a subsidiary of Bulow Holdings, an orthotic and prosthetic firm.[7] Meanwhile, the firm sold their investment in Tink's, a spray which attracts deer while deer hunting, to Arcus Hunting, another investment firm.[8]Frist served on the Board of Directors of Triad Hospitals.[5] In 2009, he was appointed to the Board of Directors of Science Applications International Corporation (SAIC), now known as Leidos, a defense corporation.[5] He has served on the Board of Directors of the Hospital Corporation of America since 2006.[1]PhilanthropyFrist serves on the Board of Directors of the Frist Foundation.[6]Personal lifeIn 1998, Frist married Julie Damgard, a Goldman Sachs employee and the daughter of John Michael Damgard, who served as the President of the Futures Industry Association.[2] They have three children.[1] They reside in Belle Meade, Tennessee, near Nashville.[9]References^ a b c d e Hospital Corporation of America: Board of Directors: THOMAS F. FRIST III^ a b c d WEDDINGS; Julie Damgard, Thomas Frist 3d, The New York Times, September 27, 1998^ SunTrust director Frist steps down, Nashville Post, September 9, 2010^ a b c d Thomas F. Frist III, Bloomberg Business^ a b c Defense contractor elects a Frist to board, Nashville Post, October 5, 2009^ a b The Frist Foundation: Directors^ Frist Capital, BCP Holdings commit $100M to orthotic practice venture, Nashville Post, January 9, 2015^ Geert De Lombaerde, Frist Capital sells hunting products venture, Nashville Post, January 9, 2015^ J.R. Lind, A glimpse at the most expensive homes in Nashville, Nashville City Paper, August 26, 2012






